> None of these really tell me how this is going to solve my problems. I don&#x27;t care if something is big, slow, and messy if it solves my problem when nothing else can.<p>My experience is that when choosing an embedded scripting language, small and clean really are first-class features.<p>When you drop a scripting engine into your app, you&#x27;re going to end up spending some time debugging into that code. You&#x27;re basically on the hook for understanding and maintaining it. The cleaner and smaller that is, the simpler your life is.<p>> The only bullet point that comes close is the one talking about it being &#x27;class-based&#x27;, but I almost never hearing someone say &quot;moving the code to classes will solve this problem&quot;.<p>Syntax is a usability feature, not a utility one. It&#x27;s almost never a question of &quot;<i>Can</i> I do this?&quot;, instead it&#x27;s, &quot;Is it easy, enjoyable, and not error-prone to do this?&quot;<p>If you&#x27;re writing object-oriented code (which many people do in scripting languages these days), I think dedicated class syntax is a real usability win for most programs.<p>The FAQ has an example. Here&#x27;s Lua:<p><pre><code>    Account = {}
    Account.__index = Account

    function Account.create(balance)
       local acnt = {}             -- our new object
       setmetatable(acnt,Account)  -- make Account handle lookup
       acnt.balance = balance      -- initialize our object
       return acnt
    end

    function Account:withdraw(amount)
       self.balance = self.balance - amount
    end

    -- create and use an Account
    acc = Account.create(1000)
    acc:withdraw(100)
</code></pre>
And here&#x27;s the same thing in Wren:<p><pre><code>    class Account {
      new(balance) { _balance = balance }
      withdraw(amount) { _balance = _balance - amount }
    }

    // create and use an Account
    var acc = new Account(100)
    acc.withdraw(100)
</code></pre>
> What problems do users that need an embedded scripting language have? Just guessing, but probably #1 is the difficulty of integrating it into their existing project (and ease of extendibility with my app).<p>Yes, the usability of the embedding API is a key piece (and one I still have to do a lot of work on). The other big ones are performance, the usability of the language itself, and the comprehensibility of the implementation.<p>The language usability is a huge one because that&#x27;s one of the main reasons you&#x27;re even using a scripting language. If the language doesn&#x27;t make it more pleasant to express your intent, you may as well just stick with C.
